    You know I bought a good
    lease with a bad title.

51:10.268 --> 51:11.600
 I got seven days to pay it off.

51:11.602 --> 51:13.536
      Two of the heirs are
       in court right now

51:13.538 --> 51:15.538
        feuding over the
       block that I want.

51:16.140 --> 51:17.807
       So renew the lease
        from both heirs,

51:17.809 --> 51:20.609
    drill it and the royalty
   money will go to the court.

51:20.611 --> 51:22.344
 Then when the suit is settled,

51:22.346 --> 51:24.313
     they'll give it to the
   rightful owner, easy-peasy.

51:24.315 --> 51:25.481
     Hell, I don't even have

51:25.483 --> 51:28.084
       the money to renew
       it from one of 'em.

51:28.086 --> 51:29.819
      Then drill it before
       the lease expires.

51:29.821 --> 51:31.120
         In seven days?

51:31.122 --> 51:34.557
     We need a partner and
    we needed one yesterday.

51:38.329 --> 51:39.528
         (mouths a name)

51:55.713 --> 51:58.848
     Mr. Naylor, my name's
     Jim McNeely, President

51:58.850 --> 52:02.218
     of McNeely Oil Company,
   can I have a word with you?

52:02.220 --> 52:03.385
     What's this all about?

52:03.387 --> 52:05.321
       Can't you see I'm
     having a meeting here?

52:08.226 --> 52:11.260
         Mr. Naylor, I'm
       about to move a rig

52:11.262 --> 52:14.797
     on the Turpin section,
  offsetting your Sheets lease.

52:14.799 --> 52:16.265
 I intend to be making a hole by

52:16.267 --> 52:18.234
 Monday unless someone stops me.

52:20.571 --> 52:22.738
        Hell, I've never
        heard of whatever

52:22.740 --> 52:25.508
    the hell company you're
  supposed to be President of.

52:28.346 --> 52:31.580
   Sir, would you like to hear
   what I have to say or not?

52:34.285 --> 52:36.452
    Guess he liked my speech.

52:41.425 --> 52:42.491
             Hello.

52:43.327 --> 52:44.260
            [Lee] Hi.

52:45.696 --> 52:50.366
    Just how much money are
   you drawing, Mrs. McNeely?

52:50.368 --> 52:53.636
   Not enough to put up with
  you clowns, that's for sure.

53:00.678 --> 53:01.677
          You're fired.

53:03.748 --> 53:05.214
              What?

53:05.216 --> 53:05.948
            Whaaaaat?

53:06.851 --> 53:07.783
          You're fired.

53:09.220 --> 53:09.952
            Oh yeah.

53:09.954 --> 53:14.723
       I'm trading you in
      for a full time wife.

53:14.725 --> 53:18.327
  You can paint up that little
 room you've been talking about.

53:18.329 --> 53:21.597
       Consul just bought
      a piece of our lease

53:21.599 --> 53:24.366
      and hired us to drill
     it, we start on Monday.

53:25.436 --> 53:27.870
       This sly son of a
      silver-tongued devil

53:27.872 --> 53:30.539
       walked over to the
       President of Consul

53:30.541 --> 53:33.209
   Petroleum and sold him the
    damn deal outta nowhere.

53:33.211 --> 53:34.977
             Ah ha.

53:34.979 --> 53:37.213
  I nailed that son of a bitch.

53:37.215 --> 53:38.614
          Yes you did.

53:38.616 --> 53:41.717
     (upbeat trumpet music)

53:41.719 --> 53:44.286
     I've got the prettiest
   girl in the state of Texas.

53:45.890 --> 53:50.960
¶ Cheers, here's to you and me ¶

53:51.762 --> 53:53.963
     ¶ Baby can't you see ¶

53:53.965 --> 53:56.865
y Jim, I've been looking at it..

53:56.867 --> 53:58.434
     It's a great prospect.

53:59.670 --> 54:02.338
           (cheering)

54:02.740 --> 54:07.343
     (upbeat big band music)

54:10.014 --> 54:12.348
            Yes Jim!

54:12.350 --> 54:13.415
           You did it!

54:29.033 --> 54:31.000
              Yes.

54:31.001 --> 54:32.968
 ¶ North, south, east or west ¶

54:32.970 --> 54:36.839
 ¶ We've got whatever it takes ¶

54:36.841 --> 54:40.542
        ¶ We'll make our
       own lucky breaks ¶

54:40.544 --> 54:44.346
         ¶ So clear the
       decks for action ¶

54:44.348 --> 54:47.683
   ¶ Guaranteed satisfaction ¶

54:47.685 --> 54:53.956
       ¶ We'll go all the
      way, stand or fall ¶

54:54.392 --> 54:57.359
          ¶ So cheers ¶

54:57.361 --> 55:00.029
       ¶ To one and all ¶

55:05.336 --> 55:08.837
        So soon, you pass
        me off that soon?

55:08.839 --> 55:12.041
      (upbeat guitar music)

55:18.949 --> 55:21.950
     (relaxed violin music)

55:50.648 --> 55:51.814
           Goddammit.

56:00.658 --> 56:02.891
   [Jim] There's only a rare
   few  of these to be found.

56:06.664 --> 56:07.930
      Now there's one less.

56:13.070 --> 56:15.938
   They'd offered it to me and
   I threw it out the window.

56:18.776 --> 56:21.944
      But you told me not
      to buy cheap leases.

56:21.946 --> 56:23.145
      So now it's my fault?

56:24.482 --> 56:26.582
       So what if you did
       buy Scurry County?

56:27.785 --> 56:29.952
   We'd be sloppy rich by now?

56:29.954 --> 56:32.554
    What would you have that
    you haven't already got?

56:32.556 --> 56:34.456
    A title like millionaire?

56:35.659 --> 56:38.660
      In case you haven't
   heard, I am a millionaire.

56:38.662 --> 56:39.595
           [Lee] Jim.

56:39.597 --> 56:44.166
      No wait, you add up
      the value of the oil

56:44.168 --> 56:47.503
     in the ground and the
     rig and the new office

56:47.505 --> 56:49.605
        building and this
     house that you live in,

56:49.607 --> 56:53.041
  subtract what I owe, there's
    a million dollars left.

56:53.043 --> 56:54.443
     And what does that do?

56:55.513 --> 56:57.112
       What are you gonna
       do with more money?

56:57.114 --> 56:59.815
       Where do you stop
         wanting, when?

57:00.885 --> 57:02.084
      When you really get
      to be a millionaire?

57:02.086 --> 57:04.153
 I am a millionaire, goddammit!

57:04.155 --> 57:05.521
      Well yippee for you.

57:17.668 --> 57:18.600
              Hey.

57:21.639 --> 57:22.571
              Say.

57:24.141 --> 57:26.108
       There's something I
       forgot to tell you.

57:27.878 --> 57:29.211
   We're moving to Fort Worth.

57:31.782 --> 57:32.714
         [Jim] Surprise.

57:34.785 --> 57:37.820
     I knew we were going, I
     just didn't know when.

57:41.158 --> 57:45.093
  (relaxed piano, violin music)

58:23.534 --> 58:26.134
    [Lee] My God, the houses
  just keep on gettin' bigger.

58:26.136 --> 58:29.071
    [Jim] Yeah and the jerks
     that live in 'em too.

58:29.073 --> 58:31.073
       Tomorrow I'm gonna
        show you the new

58:31.075 --> 58:33.609
      headquarters for the
      McNeely Oil Company.

58:34.678 --> 58:36.211
        I'm gonna kick my
       boots up on my desk

58:36.213 --> 58:38.614
       every day and make
       like a big oilman.

58:39.683 --> 58:41.083
       [Lee] When did this
         all come about?

58:41.085 --> 58:42.284
      Dent took care of it.

58:44.822 --> 58:46.822
        What do you think
         about this one?

58:46.824 --> 58:48.924
  It looks like a small castle.

58:48.926 --> 58:51.660
        They're having a
      party, there's music.

58:51.662 --> 58:52.594
               Oh.

58:53.931 --> 58:55.130
          It's for you.

58:55.132 --> 58:57.199
  But I don't know anyone here.

58:57.201 --> 58:58.667
              Yet.

58:58.669 --> 59:01.670
     This is a housewarming
     party honey, for you.

59:01.672 --> 59:04.340
              What?

59:04.341 --> 59:07.009
   This is your new castle and
  since you're the queen of it,

59:10.014 --> 59:11.280
         you get a key.

59:11.282 --> 59:13.282
    Jim, what have you done?

59:14.251 --> 59:15.651
      Don't worry about it.

59:16.620 --> 59:17.553
           We're home.

59:19.557 --> 59:22.791
     (upbeat trumpet music)

59:24.728 --> 59:27.829
        Hey y'all, howdy.

59:27.831 --> 59:29.965
     You traitorous bastard.

59:31.569 --> 59:32.668
      Lookin' great, honey.

59:35.105 --> 59:36.872
         [Jim] Charley.
           Jim, Lee.

59:37.708 --> 59:39.141
          Welcome home.

59:39.143 --> 59:41.276
  It took y'all long enough to
  get out of that dustbowl but

59:41.278 --> 59:43.712
      I trust you'll find
  yourselves comfortable here.

59:43.714 --> 59:46.048
     Excuse me gentlemen if
     I use the powder room.

59:49.753 --> 59:52.688
      Jim McNeely, welcome
      back to Fort Worth.

59:52.690 --> 59:54.823
   You sure have made quite a
   name for yourself out West.

59:54.825 --> 59:56.592
        He certainly has.

59:56.594 --> 59:58.226
   Yeah, I've done all right.

59:58.228 --> 01:00:00.295
     A far cry from the days
    on the schoolyard, right?

01:00:00.297 --> 01:00:02.998
 That was a long time ago, Jim.

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:05.233
  Charley here was just telling
  us about your latest streak.

01:00:05.235 --> 01:00:07.970
       Well, Charley tell
       'em about our last

01:00:07.972 --> 01:00:10.606
      deal that bought you
       that new Cadillac.

01:00:10.608 --> 01:00:13.241
   Maybe we'll get y'all in on
   our Reeves County prospect.

01:00:13.243 --> 01:00:16.278
     Sounds all right to me.
      [Jim] Excuse me boys,

01:00:16.280 --> 01:00:18.046
    y'all get a drink or 10.

01:00:19.350 --> 01:00:22.618
    One well, one Cadillac,
   easiest money I ever made.

01:00:36.767 --> 01:00:37.899
You still think you can struggle

01:00:37.901 --> 01:00:39.668
         along in this
      little old bungalow?

01:00:40.638 --> 01:00:42.304
    Looks like a damn museum.

01:00:42.306 --> 01:00:45.107
      Everyone's impressed,
     repulsed but impressed.

01:00:46.176 --> 01:00:48.744
       But that's what you
        wanted, isn't it?

01:00:48.746 --> 01:00:50.879
    You done good, Denty boy.

01:00:50.881 --> 01:00:52.681
        I even got you a
        little something.

01:00:54.385 --> 01:00:56.018
      Well open it, dammit.

01:00:56.020 --> 01:00:59.688
       Are you proposing?
        [Jim] You wish.

01:01:03.761 --> 01:01:06.128
           Thank you.
         For everything.

01:01:09.767 --> 01:01:12.934
   Alright. Don't go gettin'
     all sentimental on me.

01:01:14.972 --> 01:01:16.071
         I need a drink.

01:01:17.141 --> 01:01:18.073
             Buster?

01:01:21.845 --> 01:01:23.412
    [Mrs. Wales] Jim McNeely.

01:01:23.414 --> 01:01:25.814
        Hello Mrs. Wales.

01:01:25.816 --> 01:01:27.282
     You do look wonderful.

01:01:28.185 --> 01:01:29.451
         Why thank you.

01:01:29.453 --> 01:01:31.219
 You look mighty sharp yourself.

01:01:31.221 --> 01:01:33.388
   I'm so glad you invited me.

01:01:33.390 --> 01:01:35.857
      I just wish Dr. Wales
      had lived to see it.

01:01:36.827 --> 01:01:38.326
            Come on.

01:01:38.328 --> 01:01:40.429
           Let's walk.
           Yes ma'am.

01:01:41.732 --> 01:01:44.232
    It's a lovely house, Jim.

01:01:44.234 --> 01:01:45.233
        It is, isn't it?

01:01:45.235 --> 01:01:46.902
I remember it when I was a girl.

01:01:48.739 --> 01:01:50.305
 I remember a lot of things too.

01:01:51.408 --> 01:01:55.977
       Now Jim, the past
      is a long time gone.

01:01:57.081 --> 01:01:59.414
        You have done so
       magnificently well.

01:01:59.416 --> 01:02:01.883
      I'd like to think Dr.
     Wales and I were partly

01:02:01.885 --> 01:02:05.387
 responsible for giving you the
  push in the right direction.

01:02:05.389 --> 01:02:07.322
        I'd say it was a
       pretty good shove.

01:02:09.293 --> 01:02:10.759
  Now you know bitterness will

01:02:10.761 --> 01:02:13.061
       suck the pleasure
      right out of things.

01:02:16.867 --> 01:02:17.666
          How's Mazie?

01:02:17.667 --> 01:02:18.466
 I don't know how much you know.

01:02:19.503 --> 01:02:22.304
       It hasn't been all
       sunshine for Mazie.

01:02:23.240 --> 01:02:24.740
     I'm sorry to hear that.

01:02:25.375 --> 01:02:27.375
  I figured y'all had it made.

01:02:27.377 --> 01:02:31.213
    Pluto, I mean Clayton, he
   comes from such good stock.

01:02:36.520 --> 01:02:38.420
        Mrs. Wales, can I
        get you a drink?

01:02:40.124 --> 01:02:41.790
  A scotch would be wonderful.

01:02:42.426 --> 01:02:43.925
      One scotch coming up.

01:02:44.895 --> 01:02:47.229
    It is so good to see you,
    I'm so glad you're here.

01:02:48.365 --> 01:02:50.065
         Thank you, Jim.

01:02:51.902 --> 01:02:53.869
           [Ort] Jim.

01:02:53.871 --> 01:02:56.371
      You old boll-weevil.
           [Jim] Ort.

01:02:56.373 --> 01:03:00.976
    Come here, you oughta be
   mighty proud, son 'a bitch.

01:03:00.978 --> 01:03:03.011
         Save that kinda
       talk for the field.

01:03:03.013 --> 01:03:04.780
I just come to congratulate you.

01:03:04.781 --> 01:03:06.548
    I know you did, you look
    great, I love this tie.

01:03:06.550 --> 01:03:07.883
              Jim.

01:03:07.885 --> 01:03:09.151
          Here she is.

01:03:12.823 --> 01:03:13.922
        Has she changed?

01:03:13.924 --> 01:03:16.191
        Just look at her.
           Mom, stop.

01:03:16.193 --> 01:03:18.927
     You sound like you're
 exhibited a registered heifer.

01:03:20.097 --> 01:03:21.396
   It's good to see you, Jim.

01:03:23.100 --> 01:03:24.032
              Wow.

01:03:24.835 --> 01:03:26.067
 Little old Mazie Wales grew up

01:03:26.069 --> 01:03:29.104
    to be even more stunning
        than I remember.

01:03:29.106 --> 01:03:31.139
       You didn't turn out
        so bad yourself.

01:03:31.141 --> 01:03:34.009
     [Pluto] Where the hell
    did everyone get off to?

01:03:34.011 --> 01:03:35.277
            Stabber,

01:03:35.279 --> 01:03:37.512
        goddamn Stabber.

01:03:37.514 --> 01:03:39.114
             Pluto.

01:03:39.116 --> 01:03:42.884
   Me and this man, we had us
   some times didn't we Jim?

01:03:47.124 --> 01:03:49.291
         I've had myself
       some bad luck, Jim.

01:03:50.561 --> 01:03:53.295
   Hey, we gots to go and talk
     somewhere, huh brother?

01:03:55.299 --> 01:03:56.898
    Let's all go get a drink.

01:03:59.002 --> 01:04:02.137
        Pluto, you still
       drinking, whiskey?

01:04:02.139 --> 01:04:04.206
     [Pluto] I'm never not.

01:04:24.394 --> 01:04:27.395
    [Mazie] I should've sent
    you a plant or something.

01:04:27.397 --> 01:04:29.598
      But I do have another
     little present for you.

01:04:31.401 --> 01:04:32.467
      I've been saving it.

01:04:35.072 --> 01:04:36.271
   Don't open 'til Christmas.

01:04:36.273 --> 01:04:38.206
        That Christmas is
        ancient history.

01:04:40.611 --> 01:04:44.012
   I am so happy for you, Jim
    and I know that you have

01:04:44.014 --> 01:04:46.882
    a wonderful wife now and
    I can't wait to meet her

01:04:46.884 --> 01:04:49.618
   and do everything I can to
  make sure she likes it here.

01:04:52.890 --> 01:04:55.657
     You might as well start
      now, here she comes.

01:04:55.659 --> 01:04:57.359
 Honey, come here for a minute.

01:04:58.495 --> 01:05:00.295
       I want you to meet
         a very special

01:05:00.297 --> 01:05:01.897
friend of mine, this is Mazie...

01:05:03.233 --> 01:05:05.450
             LeMane!

01:05:05.451 --> 01:05:07.668
     Hi Mazie, Lee McNeely,
     it's nice to meet you.

01:05:07.671 --> 01:05:09.471
It so nice to meet you too, Lee.

01:05:09.473 --> 01:05:11.306
     Welcome to Fort Worth.

01:05:11.308 --> 01:05:12.674
           Thank you.

01:05:12.676 --> 01:05:15.443
       Sorry to interrupt,
     there are two gentlemen

01:05:15.445 --> 01:05:17.946
    who seem to have settled
       into an all night

01:05:17.948 --> 01:05:21.483
   drinking game into what I
   presume to be our bedroom.

01:05:21.485 --> 01:05:23.151
     Do you think they would
       mind terribly if I

01:05:23.153 --> 01:05:26.288
      put on my pajamas and
    slipped quietly into bed?

01:05:26.290 --> 01:05:28.089
         (Mazie laughs)

01:05:28.091 --> 01:05:29.624
        She's funny too.

01:05:29.626 --> 01:05:31.159
           I like her.

01:05:31.161 --> 01:05:33.094
  I'll take care of it, honey.

01:05:33.096 --> 01:05:36.097
   Jim, I think it's time you
    kicked us all out and I

01:05:36.099 --> 01:05:38.500
 will get to know this wonderful
   wife of yours soon enough.

01:05:38.502 --> 01:05:40.001
    That's very nice of you.

01:05:41.104 --> 01:05:42.103
       I'll lead you out.

01:05:43.206 --> 01:05:44.205
        [Jim] All right.

01:05:44.207 --> 01:05:46.441
 I'll be out there in a minute.

01:05:46.443 --> 01:05:47.642
       Good show, old man.

01:05:49.079 --> 01:05:50.011
      [Jim] Good to see ya.

01:05:58.155 --> 01:06:02.057
     (festive trumpet music)

01:06:02.059 --> 01:06:03.291
       [Lee] Two diamonds.

01:06:03.293 --> 01:06:05.360
 You gotta beat three, sweetie.

01:06:05.362 --> 01:06:06.695
      This country bumpkin
        here is used to

01:06:06.697 --> 01:06:09.531
   throwin' dice with cowboys,
       not playing bridge.

01:06:09.533 --> 01:06:11.166
            Cowboys?

01:06:11.168 --> 01:06:14.002
      Well that sounds fun.
            (laughs)

01:06:15.339 --> 01:06:17.238
    [Woman] You kill me, Lee.

01:06:23.647 --> 01:06:24.713
          I admire you.

01:06:25.716 --> 01:06:27.182
               Me?

01:06:27.184 --> 01:06:28.249
          Why on earth?

01:06:29.486 --> 01:06:31.753
      Havin' the courage to
    leave your first husband.

01:06:31.755 --> 01:06:35.190
   I mean weren't you worried
     about people talking?

01:06:36.426 --> 01:06:39.327
   We didn't stick around to
 find out what people would say

01:06:39.329 --> 01:06:42.063
 or do, it all happened so fast.

01:06:42.065 --> 01:06:43.398
[Mazie] way you describe feeling

01:06:43.400 --> 01:06:46.267
      back then, that's the
      way I feel right now.

01:06:46.269 --> 01:06:47.769
               Oh.

01:06:47.771 --> 01:06:51.172
      Mazie, it was so much
        different for me.

01:06:51.174 --> 01:06:53.174
   Look at all that you have.

01:06:53.176 --> 01:06:55.744
 You live in a city, the people.

01:06:55.746 --> 01:06:57.679
     Pluto, I mean Clayton,

01:06:57.681 --> 01:07:01.583
     he is such a fine young
     man from a good family.

01:07:01.585 --> 01:07:03.485
    Look at this pity party.

01:07:03.487 --> 01:07:08.289
    Shake it off, that's what
    I do and drink of course.

01:07:14.297 --> 01:07:15.263
           Thank you.

01:07:28.311 --> 01:07:30.378
         It's strange to
        be served dinner.

01:07:33.683 --> 01:07:36.084
         [Jim] Well get
       used to it, sugar.

01:07:36.086 --> 01:07:39.320
     I don't know what to do
     in this big house, Jim.

01:07:39.322 --> 01:07:40.722
 Can I come work in the office?

01:07:40.724 --> 01:07:42.323
    How's your new accountant
    doing, does he need help?

01:07:42.325 --> 01:07:46.361
        No, my wife's not
    working at a damn office.

01:07:46.363 --> 01:07:49.731
    Besides, I thought you'd
  like to be a lady of leisure.

01:07:49.733 --> 01:07:52.567
      Leisure and boredom
    seem to go hand in hand.

01:07:52.569 --> 01:07:56.471
     Leisure and business,
   that's how deals are made.

01:07:57.674 --> 01:08:00.642
      Speaking of, Pluto's
     going to drop by later

01:08:00.644 --> 01:08:04.212
   for a drink, says he's got
  an ace of a deal to show me.

01:08:04.214 --> 01:08:06.548
    I thought we could have
    some time alone tonight.

01:08:06.550 --> 01:08:07.682
            For once.

01:08:07.684 --> 01:08:09.684
      He's my old oil field
        buddy, you know?

01:08:09.686 --> 01:08:13.088
  You get mighty close working
    on those gangs together.

01:08:14.424 --> 01:08:16.524
        Oh, and Mazie's
       tagging along too.

01:08:19.595 --> 01:08:20.528
               Oh?

01:08:22.099 --> 01:08:24.698
  I have to say, I didn't know
    how I feel about Mazie.

01:08:24.701 --> 01:08:28.236
       But I do like her,
       she's down to earth

01:08:28.238 --> 01:08:30.305
beneath all those fancy clothes.

01:08:30.307 --> 01:08:32.372
  She's a good girl, harmless.

01:08:33.676 --> 01:08:36.144
        I'm glad you two
       are getting along.

01:08:36.145 --> 01:08:37.679
     (festive trumpet music)

01:08:37.680 --> 01:08:39.346
          I win again.

01:08:39.349 --> 01:08:42.149
     Hey Lee, why don't you
     come over here and give

01:08:42.152 --> 01:08:44.419
      a girl a hand taking
    down these knuckleheads?

01:08:45.755 --> 01:08:50.125
     I gotta say it, I hate
   cards and I'm going to bed.

01:08:51.495 --> 01:08:53.161
    Don't be so sour, sugar.

01:08:53.162 --> 01:08:56.531
       I'm not being sour,
         I'm just tired.

01:08:56.533 --> 01:08:57.465
              Hey.

01:08:58.435 --> 01:08:59.367
              Hey.

01:09:00.203 --> 01:09:02.537
  I can send them home, honey.

01:09:03.874 --> 01:09:05.206
              Nah.

01:09:05.207 --> 01:09:07.207
        Y'all are having
      fun, I am being sour.

01:09:07.210 --> 01:09:08.376
      You enjoy yourselves.

01:09:09.613 --> 01:09:11.212
        Goodnight y'all.
    [Pluto] Goodnight, honey.

01:09:11.214 --> 01:09:12.881
        [Jim] Goodnight.
       All right Stabber,

01:09:13.884 --> 01:09:17.385
      come and deal 'em up
     you goddamn field hand.

01:09:17.386 --> 01:09:19.270
      Let's beat this girl.

01:09:19.272 --> 01:09:21.156
           Oh please.
     [Pluto] She's cheating.

01:09:21.158 --> 01:09:24.792
       (telephone ringing)

01:09:24.794 --> 01:09:27.295
             Hello.
      [Jim] Hey sweetheart.

01:09:27.296 --> 01:09:30.598
  Pack your bags, we're going
 to West Texas for the weekend.

01:09:30.600 --> 01:09:34.836
  West Texas, where, just you
  and me, what should I bring?

01:09:34.837 --> 01:09:37.337
       [Jim] Oh hell, just
       bring a toothbrush.

01:09:37.340 --> 01:09:39.307
    Do some cowgirl shopping
       over at Lettie's.

01:09:39.309 --> 01:09:41.475
     I'll pick you up at 11.
        - Are you crazy?

01:09:41.478 --> 01:09:43.444
       That's in an hour.
        [Jim] Yeah well,

01:09:43.446 --> 01:09:45.747
        we'll arrive just
       in time for dinner.

01:09:45.749 --> 01:09:46.613
              Jim!

01:09:46.616 --> 01:09:49.917
     (country violin music)

01:09:58.695 --> 01:10:01.196
        Upgrade us to the
       Presidential Suite.

01:10:01.198 --> 01:10:02.697
        I mean if you're
       gonna do it right,

01:10:02.699 --> 01:10:04.332
         you gotta do it
       right, right sugar?

01:10:04.334 --> 01:10:05.667
        Sounds wonderful.

01:10:05.669 --> 01:10:07.602
        [Pluto] Stabber.

01:10:07.604 --> 01:10:09.938
     [Mazie] What took y'all
      so long to get here?

01:10:11.341 --> 01:10:13.341
            Hey Lee.
     I should've warned you.

01:10:13.343 --> 01:10:15.310
         [Mazie] Hi Jim.
           [Lee] Jim,

01:10:15.312 --> 01:10:17.445
    this is a business trip?

01:10:17.447 --> 01:10:19.681
 Honey, it's an everything trip.

01:10:21.218 --> 01:10:23.551
  Let's go check out our suite.

01:10:29.492 --> 01:10:32.293
         (gunshot booms)

01:10:34.631 --> 01:10:38.733
 [Jim] Gentlemen, we've drilled
    nine prospects together.

01:10:38.735 --> 01:10:41.002
  Five were dry, four produced.

01:10:41.004 --> 01:10:44.005
        The one in Reagan
      County is just so-so.

01:10:44.007 --> 01:10:46.007
      I wouldn't recommend
    drilling any more there.

01:10:46.009 --> 01:10:48.743
    We'll just, we'll farm it
    out to another operator.

01:10:49.813 --> 01:10:51.546
         What we should
       all be thinking is

01:10:51.548 --> 01:10:53.348
   looking for something with
   a little more juice in it.

01:10:53.350 --> 01:10:54.482
  How long you think it's gonna

01:10:54.484 --> 01:10:56.017
      take for that Reagan
        well to pay out?

01:10:56.019 --> 01:10:58.953
  At current production rates,
  about three and a half years.

01:10:58.955 --> 01:11:00.855
       Oh, well that don't
         sound too bad.

01:11:02.359 --> 01:11:03.958
   Why can't we just drill the
  rest of that lease ourselves?

01:11:03.960 --> 01:11:05.760
 The Reagan well's cuttin' water

01:11:06.830 --> 01:11:08.963
      and history's taught
     me when you get water,

01:11:08.965 --> 01:11:10.865
        that water's just
         gonna increase.

01:11:12.302 --> 01:11:14.802
    I don't make money if you
     boys don't make money.

01:11:14.804 --> 01:11:18.539
   Our oil in the ground today
   will produce hefty returns.

01:11:18.541 --> 01:11:20.942
      Hell, we might even
    find another East Texas.

01:11:20.944 --> 01:11:22.410
        Or Scurry County.

01:11:25.682 --> 01:11:27.415
         I'm gonna drill
      these wells on my own

01:11:27.417 --> 01:11:29.484
    or with other partners if
     y'all ain't interested.

01:11:29.486 --> 01:11:32.754
  Hold on a minute Jim, nobody
  said we weren't interested.

01:11:32.756 --> 01:11:34.022
              Good.

01:11:34.024 --> 01:11:37.292
     After this next string
       of wildcats, we'll

01:11:37.294 --> 01:11:41.496
 take that safari trip courtesy
   of McNeely Oil of course.

01:11:41.498 --> 01:11:42.697
           All right.

01:11:42.699 --> 01:11:44.032
       I don't know if you
       gentlemen know this

01:11:44.034 --> 01:11:45.833
      but one of my life's
        great ambitions

01:11:45.835 --> 01:11:47.935
        is to kill every
      species that exists.

01:11:47.937 --> 01:11:49.570
 I got about 100 of 'em so far.

01:11:50.807 --> 01:11:53.508
    Let me know when you get
    around to homo sapiens,

01:11:53.510 --> 01:11:56.377
         so I can hide.
         (men chuckle)

01:11:56.379 --> 01:11:57.812
     My wife's a comedienne.

01:11:57.814 --> 01:12:01.716
    Oh Jim, I have been dying
      to kill an elephant.

01:12:01.718 --> 01:12:04.819
       Honey, I'll fix it
        so that you kill

01:12:04.821 --> 01:12:07.488
        the biggest damn
       elephant in Africa.

01:12:07.490 --> 01:12:09.757
    You could mount his foot
     for an umbrella stand,

01:12:09.759 --> 01:12:11.326
    paint his toenails gold.

01:12:12.529 --> 01:12:14.662
     Dent, line up a safari.

01:12:16.066 --> 01:12:18.933
   You should come too, we'll
  need somebody to mix drinks.

01:12:21.037 --> 01:12:21.969
           Yes B'wana.

01:12:24.908 --> 01:12:28.576
   [Jim] Well boys, this next
  string's gonna be real nice.

01:12:30.347 --> 01:12:33.581
   Don't worry too much about
   this circus, little buddy.

01:12:33.583 --> 01:12:35.683
       There are very few
    people in this jolly new

01:12:35.685 --> 01:12:39.053
  milieu of ours who live lives
    of any real significance.

01:12:39.889 --> 01:12:41.889
  All our new playmates seem to

01:12:41.891 --> 01:12:44.359
     dedicate their lives to
     pleasuring themselves.

01:12:44.361 --> 01:12:47.362
       Sybarites, stay up
        late, drink deep

01:12:47.364 --> 01:12:49.364
       from the laughing
      waters and burn your

01:12:49.366 --> 01:12:51.899
       incense at sunset
       to the God of Fun.

01:12:53.370 --> 01:12:54.068
          Count me out.

01:12:55.638 --> 01:12:58.840
     (tepid ensemble music)

01:13:00.944 --> 01:13:03.111
     The cabbie's loaded up.

01:13:04.147 --> 01:13:06.147
        I'm too close to
      home to not go see it

01:13:07.784 --> 01:13:09.150
 and by golly, close that deal.

01:13:09.152 --> 01:13:10.084
          I always do.

01:13:11.521 --> 01:13:14.389
      I got a good feeling
    about this next prospect.

01:13:14.391 --> 01:13:15.890
It might be enough to retire on.

01:13:16.793 --> 01:13:18.860
     Wouldn't that be nice?

01:13:20.497 --> 01:13:21.763
      Someday we will, hon.

01:13:22.565 --> 01:13:23.498
              Hey.

01:13:27.637 --> 01:13:28.536
             I know.

01:13:31.808 --> 01:13:34.675
       Drive safe sugar,
     I'll see you tomorrow.

01:13:34.677 --> 01:13:35.710
          Tell dad hi.

01:13:58.868 --> 01:14:02.203
     This old knee's givin'
      me a little trouble.

01:14:02.205 --> 01:14:06.007
   But nothing an ice pack and
    a shot of rye can't fix.

01:14:08.812 --> 01:14:10.445
     Enough about my health.

01:14:12.715 --> 01:14:13.648
            Spill it.

01:14:14.784 --> 01:14:15.750
          What's wrong?

01:14:16.886 --> 01:14:17.952
  You didn't drive all the way

01:14:17.954 --> 01:14:19.687
out here just to make me dinner.

01:14:20.623 --> 01:14:22.457
It's an empty life we're living.

01:14:23.726 --> 01:14:27.028
    All these men he used to
   know now swarming around us

01:14:28.064 --> 01:14:29.931
         just because he
       struck a few wells.

01:14:31.000 --> 01:14:33.100
     But he's trying to be a
     part of something that

01:14:34.170 --> 01:14:38.072
    I just don't care about.
    - Oil men want respect.

01:14:39.075 --> 01:14:40.575
         It's a disease.

01:14:42.512 --> 01:14:45.646
       It makes most crazy
       and others crooked.

01:14:45.648 --> 01:14:48.082
    Breaks the hearts of the
    strong and rewards a few

01:14:48.084 --> 01:14:53.154
   lucky ones with wealth and
  power beyond their deserving.

01:14:53.156 --> 01:14:55.656
       Jim thinks he lost
       his luck at Scurry.

01:14:57.894 --> 01:14:58.993
          Maybe he did.

01:14:59.863 --> 01:15:01.696
Help him find his luck, darling.

01:15:03.199 --> 01:15:07.602
   Do that and you'll both be
   necessary to one another.

01:15:09.606 --> 01:15:13.274
  (tepid piano, trumpet music)

01:15:25.221 --> 01:15:29.156
       (singing in French)

01:15:48.811 --> 01:15:50.211
           [Mazie] Oh.

01:15:50.213 --> 01:15:51.145
              Jim.

01:15:52.048 --> 01:15:54.248
            (moaning)

01:16:02.091 --> 01:16:03.624
         (Mazie screams)

01:16:18.808 --> 01:16:20.107
            Nothing?

01:16:20.109 --> 01:16:21.809
        What the hell do
      you mean by nothing?

01:16:21.811 --> 01:16:23.210
   She doesn't want anything.

01:16:24.213 --> 01:16:26.681
    Not the house, no money.

01:16:26.683 --> 01:16:27.949
        Just the divorce.

01:16:28.985 --> 01:16:30.284
        She's got a legal
      right to what's hers.

01:16:30.286 --> 01:16:32.153
      She said she can work

01:16:32.155 --> 01:16:37.091
     and you'll need all the
  money you have and then some.

01:16:37.093 --> 01:16:38.125
              What?

01:16:38.127 --> 01:16:39.894
  What the hell does that mean?

01:16:39.896 --> 01:16:42.296
        Listen, you find
       out what I'm worth

01:16:42.298 --> 01:16:44.231
      and she'll damn sure
       take half of that.

01:16:44.233 --> 01:16:46.267
    You go back and lay that
     on the line right now.

01:16:46.269 --> 01:16:47.702
        Why don't you go?

01:16:47.704 --> 01:16:50.004
  I sent word I wanted to meet.

01:16:50.006 --> 01:16:51.606
 What else am I supposed to do?

01:16:51.608 --> 01:16:54.141
  In the spot you're in buddy,
   you don't send emissaries.

01:16:54.143 --> 01:16:55.343
You get over there, you get down

01:16:55.345 --> 01:16:58.012
       on your knees and
      beg for forgiveness.

01:16:58.014 --> 01:17:00.047
      Unless of course you
       want this divorce.

01:17:10.026 --> 01:17:13.094
       (soft violin tones)

01:17:31.014 --> 01:17:32.413
           (knocking)

01:17:35.718 --> 01:17:37.985
        [Lee] Who is it?

01:17:37.987 --> 01:17:39.086
       [Jim] It's me, Lee.

01:17:46.229 --> 01:17:49.964
        What do you want?

01:17:49.966 --> 01:17:51.098
      [Jim] I want to talk.

01:17:53.403 --> 01:17:55.102
  What do you wanna talk about?

01:17:56.873 --> 01:17:59.006
     I didn't mean to hurt
     you, it just happened.

01:17:59.008 --> 01:18:01.909
    It's just stupid drunken
     behavior, that's all.

01:18:03.279 --> 01:18:05.146
        You've loved her
       since she left you.

01:18:05.148 --> 01:18:06.714
               No.

01:18:06.716 --> 01:18:07.765
               No.

01:18:07.766 --> 01:18:08.815
 [Lee] This is exactly what you

01:18:08.818 --> 01:18:10.184
         wanted and you
       damn well know it.

01:18:11.421 --> 01:18:13.821
    Just get outta here so we
     can get this over with.

01:18:16.426 --> 01:18:19.193
   I've suffered long enough,
      you son of a bitch.

01:18:20.697 --> 01:18:23.898
      (somber violin music)

01:18:30.073 --> 01:18:31.939
It's over now, I'm done with it.

01:18:35.144 --> 01:18:37.044
       Please, I love you.
         [Lee] Go away.

01:18:38.114 --> 01:18:39.180
         Leave me alone.

01:18:40.149 --> 01:18:42.016
 I never want to see you again.

01:19:23.226 --> 01:19:26.427
      (somber violin music)

01:19:35.171 --> 01:19:38.038
        (Mazie laughing)

01:19:50.219 --> 01:19:53.420
      (mechanical creaking)

01:19:57.960 --> 01:19:59.026
           Goddammit.

01:20:00.530 --> 01:20:04.498
    Shut this son of a bitch
  down right now, we're empty.

01:20:04.500 --> 01:20:06.333
   This is my eighth dry well

01:20:06.335 --> 01:20:08.369
         in a row and it
       better be the last.

01:20:08.371 --> 01:20:11.405
  Shit Jim, you say that like
 I'm a rock-sniffin' geologist.

01:20:11.407 --> 01:20:14.508
  I ain't nothin' but a two-bit
   pie-playing son of a bitch.

01:20:15.978 --> 01:20:18.879
 I told you all not to eat that
  bone-in chicken on the rig.

01:20:20.917 --> 01:20:21.849
            Bad luck.

01:20:23.486 --> 01:20:24.385
            Bad luck.

01:20:24.387 --> 01:20:27.521
      (somber violin music)

01:20:27.523 --> 01:20:31.258
      [Jim] You didn't wish
      me a happy birthday.

01:20:31.260 --> 01:20:32.893
      Happy birthday, Jim.

01:20:35.932 --> 01:20:36.864
             Happy.

01:20:39.168 --> 01:20:42.870
     It's a stupid word, it
     doesn't mean anything.

01:20:42.872 --> 01:20:47.241
[Jim] You measure it by success.
  - Successful birthday then.

01:20:47.243 --> 01:20:49.844
A man who owes $3 million and is

01:20:49.846 --> 01:20:52.213
only 36 has gotta be successful.

01:20:53.282 --> 01:20:54.949
      I wouldn't ride that
        theory too long.

01:20:54.951 --> 01:20:57.151
      So what if we hadn't
    found another East Texas,

01:20:57.153 --> 01:20:59.153
 we got reserves in the ground.

01:20:59.155 --> 01:21:02.556
 And our investors are starting
    to doubt those reserves.

01:21:02.558 --> 01:21:05.526
       Look, I like risks
     just as much as you do

01:21:05.528 --> 01:21:07.261
      but sometimes I wish
     you'd let some of these

01:21:07.263 --> 01:21:09.597
      deals pay out before
      we get in any deeper.

01:21:09.599 --> 01:21:11.999
     Stop being so neurotic.

01:21:12.001 --> 01:21:14.034
  We'll hit a sweet spot soon.

01:21:15.271 --> 01:21:16.570
    I'm just being realistic

01:21:18.107 --> 01:21:20.074
        and I wish you'd
       take off that tire.

01:21:20.076 --> 01:21:21.275
  It makes me feel like I'm one

01:21:21.277 --> 01:21:23.410
         heartbeat away
       from unemployment.

01:21:23.412 --> 01:21:27.014
   Ah hell Denty boy, I've had
   too much fun puttin' it on.

01:21:27.016 --> 01:21:30.017
     Besides, I got a heart

01:21:30.019 --> 01:21:32.353
      that's stronger than
      bull rhinoceros hide.

01:21:35.358 --> 01:21:38.025
      You know it's Lee's
   birthday in a couple days.

01:21:38.027 --> 01:21:40.361
     Send her some flowers,
   see if she needs anything.

01:21:40.363 --> 01:21:41.629
     Already taken care of.

01:21:45.034 --> 01:21:47.401
       Now there's a gift
        worth the wait.

01:21:47.403 --> 01:21:49.370
Isn't it lovely to be married to

01:21:49.372 --> 01:21:52.306
        a man who buys me
    presents on his birthday?

01:21:54.243 --> 01:21:55.476
    Are you boys ready to go?

01:21:56.412 --> 01:21:57.378
           I'm ready.

01:21:58.915 --> 01:22:00.547
   [Mazie] I love my bracelet.

01:22:01.951 --> 01:22:05.219
     (anxious violin tones)

01:22:09.325 --> 01:22:10.991
  The Bison stock's done well.

01:22:12.194 --> 01:22:15.029
      It sounds like you've
      got a nice nest egg.

01:22:16.632 --> 01:22:17.631
  They don't care a damn about

01:22:17.633 --> 01:22:20.434
a geologist who put in 20 years.

01:22:20.436 --> 01:22:23.037
   I'll be scratchin' by just
     to make my retirement.

01:22:24.307 --> 01:22:26.540
       Somebody somewhere
     must owe you something.

01:22:29.345 --> 01:22:31.478
        I'm standing here
        with my hand out,

01:22:31.480 --> 01:22:33.113
  waiting for the mana to drop.

01:22:34.350 --> 01:22:35.950
   I got news for you, buddy.

01:22:36.953 --> 01:22:37.685
        Mana don't drop.

01:22:39.055 --> 01:22:41.088
You gotta reach up and pluck it.

01:22:43.059 --> 01:22:44.291
     I don't know how, Jim.

01:22:45.161 --> 01:22:46.226
       Never been able to.

01:22:48.164 --> 01:22:51.398
      This whole country's
    riddles with damn holes.

01:22:53.502 --> 01:22:55.602
Every time they drill a new one,

01:22:55.604 --> 01:22:57.404
  that's one less place to try.

01:22:59.241 --> 01:23:00.975
  I'm tired of drilling blind.

01:23:02.144 --> 01:23:04.578
     I got the rigs, I know
     where to get the money

01:23:06.048 --> 01:23:08.515
   and I can drill better than
  anyone in this goddamn state.

01:23:09.518 --> 01:23:10.451
             But...

01:23:11.287 --> 01:23:12.686
  I gotta know where to drill.

01:23:17.193 --> 01:23:18.325
        You tell me where

01:23:19.662 --> 01:23:23.230
    and you will never draw
   another poor breath again.

01:23:24.734 --> 01:23:26.734
      Am I being too subtle
         for you, Barry?

01:23:26.736 --> 01:23:27.668
               No.

01:23:29.238 --> 01:23:31.005
  You're not being subtle, Jim.

01:23:31.007 --> 01:23:34.241
     It sounds like you're
     talkin' about larceny.

01:23:37.713 --> 01:23:40.447
    [Jim] It's just a little
     map with a dot on it.

01:23:43.252 --> 01:23:47.187
  (anxious violin, piano music)

01:23:55.364 --> 01:23:58.098
         (Lee laughing)

01:23:58.534 --> 01:24:00.634
       Baby, are you okay?

01:24:02.304 --> 01:24:04.071
          Never better.

01:24:04.073 --> 01:24:05.439
       I was beginning to
      look like a ragdoll,

01:24:05.441 --> 01:24:08.308
    so I had to go shopping.

01:24:08.310 --> 01:24:11.345
 The Neiman's card was declined
    but I just paid in cash.

01:24:12.214 --> 01:24:13.814
 Buy whatever the hell you need.

01:24:15.584 --> 01:24:16.517
              Jim.

01:24:19.488 --> 01:24:22.656
    This house is a far cry
  from Bowie Street, ain't it?

01:24:24.160 --> 01:24:25.626
     Jim, what's wrong baby?

01:24:28.564 --> 01:24:32.433
  (somber violin, piano music)

01:24:48.350 --> 01:24:51.618
     Good morning, sunshine.
      This won't wash, Jim.

01:24:51.620 --> 01:24:53.587
       Leave Barry Wakely
      out of your schemes.

01:24:53.589 --> 01:24:55.089
       You can do whatever
        the hell you want

01:24:55.091 --> 01:24:57.291
         with Bison but
       leave Barry alone.

01:24:58.394 --> 01:25:00.394
       It's funny how it
       comes full circle.

01:25:00.396 --> 01:25:02.763
      You feeling sorry for
       poor old Bison Oil

01:25:02.765 --> 01:25:04.665
     Company that's got more
     money than Uncle Sugar.

01:25:04.667 --> 01:25:06.166
 You can't wreck a man like that

